"auto" class=3D"body markup"><p>I joined Richard Hanania for a deep dive in=
to the strange and surreal films of the late David Lynch, one of the most u=
nique filmmakers of recent times. We talk about =E2=80=9CMulholland Drive=
=E2=80=9D (2001) and =E2=80=9CInland Empire=E2=80=9D (2006) and why one is =
mesmerizing while the other feels like cinematic torture. If you enjoy diss=
ecting films that refuse to give easy answers, this conversation is for you=
. Many spoilers throughout. </p><p>Some topics we cover:</p><ul><li><p>=E2=
=80=9CMulholland Drive=E2=80=9D came out in 2001. Richard and I speak about=
 how Hollywood's portrayal of lesbians in the early 2000s reflects a very d=
ifferent cultural moment compared to today.</p></li><li><p>Some tangents on=
 =E2=80=9CBrokeback Mountain=E2=80=9D (2005) and other gay portrayals of th=
at era</p></li><li><p>Why =E2=80=9CMulholland Drive=E2=80=9D works despite =
its bizarre dream logic, and why =E2=80=9CInland Empire=E2=80=9D is just a =
mess.</p></li><li><p>The cowboy test in =E2=80=9CMulholland Drive.=E2=80=9D=
 If you see him once, you did good. Twice, you did bad. What does it mean?<=
/p></li><li><p>Richard shares his experience driving down Mulholland Drive =
and how the geography of Los Angeles shapes its mystique.</p></li><li><p>We=
 break down the Harvey Weinstein subtext in Hollywood movies, including a w=
ild meme about Quentin Tarantino that=E2=80=99s very on the nose.</p></li><=
/ul><div class=3D"paywall-jump" data-component-name=3D"PaywallToDOM"></div>=
<ul><li><p>Was =E2=80=9CMulholland Drive=E2=80=9D all just a dream? Did Dia=
ne really kill Camilla, or is there another way to interpret the movie? We =
debate different theories.</p></li><li><p>We get into Justin Theroux=E2=80=
=99s character in Mulholland Drive=E2=80=94what does his arc mean, and is h=
e actually a part of Diane=E2=80=99s psyche?</p></li><li><p>David Lynch lov=
es mystery, but did he even have a concrete answer to what happens in Mulho=
lland Drive? Or is it all just meant to be ambiguous?</p></li><li><p>That b=
izarre audition scene=E2=80=94is it a critique of Hollywood=E2=80=99s preda=
tory culture or something even darker?</p></li><li><p>Silencio! The club sc=
ene is unsettling, mesmerizing, and somehow central to the movie=E2=80=99s =
dream logic. We discuss what it might mean. </p></li><li><p>The symbolism o=
f the dumpster monster behind the diner=E2=80=94one of the most terrifying =
moments in the film. </p></li><li><p>We debate whether Diane and Betty=E2=
=80=99s identities blur because of subconscious guilt, or if there=E2=80=99=
s another explanation. </p></li><li><p>Betty's world is more "real" than Di=
ane's=E2=80=94why does the dream feel coherent while the supposed reality i=
s surreal and chaotic?</p></li><li><p>We then shift over to =E2=80=9CInland=
 Empire=E2=80=9D which was just about unwatchable, in my view. I share my v=
ery speculative opinion that the whole movie might be a woman=E2=80=99s fan=
tasy of stardom and infidelity, and how it unravels. </p></li><li><p>The Lo=
st Girl=E2=80=99s storyline mirrors Nikki=E2=80=99s, suggesting a cycle of =
despair and entrapment=E2=80=94is she another version of Nikki, or a past s=
elf?</p></li><li><p><span>=E2=80=9CInland Empire=E2=80=9D is </span><a href=
=3D"https://www.nytimes.com/2025/01/16/movies/david-lynch-dead.html" rel=3D=
"">described</a><span> as "willfully abstruse" and "blandly inscrutable" by=
 the </span><em>New York Times</em><span> so Richard and I were not alone i=
n our thoughts on the film</span></p></li><li><p>The moment where Nikki "di=
es" in the street, then the camera pulls back to reveal it was all a movie =
scene. We talk about whether this is Lynch questioning our ability to separ=
ate fiction from reality. </p></li><li><p>The rabbits remain one of the fil=
m=E2=80=99s biggest mysteries=E2=80=94are they symbols of the uncanny, dome=
stic monotony, or just Lynch throwing the audience into deeper confusion?</=
p></li></ul><p>Join me for my next live video in the app.</p><div class=3D"=
